PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:Market Tone: Cautious ahead of Bernanke press conference. Dollar mixed, Treasurys lower, oil slightly higher, gold little changedOvernight Action: BP Net Profit Rises; S&P Changes Japan Outlook to Negative;Watch for: Fed rate decision and press conference,  earnings from Ebay, Starbucks, Boeing, ConocoPhillipsThe Breakfast BriefingToday, all eyes will go to the Bearded One.Federal Reserve Chairman Ben Bernanke will face the scribes in a first-ever press conference at 2:15 p.m. EDT. The Fed says the press conference is aimed at increasing transparency. It?s more likely to be a tour de force in sleep-inducing obfuscation.The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed?s policy group, will issue its statement at 1230 p.m. EDT, ahead of Big Ben?s 2:15 p.m. EDT date with the press. It is difficult to imagine that Big Ben will break new ground at the microphone, but there?s always hope. Jean-Claude Trichet, head of the European Central Bank, used a press briefing to signal that the ECB planned to raise rates this month, which it did early this month. (The ECB, like other central banks, has held press briefings for years.)The dollar?s recent weakness ? the dollar index is at a three-year low and the euro is at a fresh 52-week high ? underscores the belief that the Fed is in no rush to tighten its extraordinarily loose monetary policy. Our friends at Real Time Economics offer a nifty primer on how to interpret the words and phrases of Big Ben. (The over/under betting line for number of chuckles Big Ben gets: three.)The Fed, in its statement, is expected to say it will finish its $600 billion quantitative easing program (QE2) on schedule in June. It is also not expected to raise too many alarms about looming interest-rate moves. The Fed-funds futures sees only a 26% chance that the Fed will raise rates to 0.5% by next February.As investors fidget about what the Bearded One might say, earnings will come in full force once again. On Tuesday, strong earnings from 3M, Ford Motor, Delta Air Lines and UPS helped set a robust tone from the opening bell.The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 115.49 to 12595.37, its highest close since June 5, 2008. The Nasdaq Composite jumped 21.66 to 2847.54, its highest close since Oct. 31, 2007. And the S&P 500 gained 11.99 to 1347.24, its best close since June 17, 2008.On Wednesday, earnings will come from all directions, with energy and aerospace dominating.On the energy front, Baker Hughes, Cabot Oil & Gas, BP, ConocoPhillips, ENI, Hess Corp. and National Oil Well Varco report. Energy companies have reported strong earnings, boosted by rising oil prices. Boeing, General Dynamics and Northrop Grumman report on the aerospace side. Lockheed Martin reported solid earnings Tuesday; its shares rose more than 2%.Other notable earnings: Norfolk Southern, Whirlpool, Las Vegas Sands, Akamai, Baidu, Dr. Pepper Snapple, Green Mountain Coffee Roasters, eBay, Credit Suisse, Southern Co., and Barrick Gold. #text: Micron Technology

reported a wider-than-expected fiscal third-quarter loss as the memory-chip maker said sales dropped 55 percent. The company reported a loss of $301 million, or 50 cents a share, compared with 15 cents in the year-ago quarter. Results include a pre-tax inventory write-down of approximately $260 million. Analysts expected a loss of 15 cents, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. It was not immediately clear whether First Call's figure accounted for a write-down. Ahead of the report, shares of the memory-chip maker rose 87 cents, or 2.4 percent, at $37.71 but retreated to $36.45 in third-market trading.
